Paxilline (10 ìÒ) blocked the fAHP (Fig. 4A and B) and slowed the last 2Ï3 of the spike repolarization (Fig. 4E). Like IbTX, paxilline also broadened all spikes in the train, and reduced the broadening from the 1st to the 3rd spike (Fig. 4C and D, I and J): from 52·2 ± 9·2 % in normal medium to 21·7 ± 5·6 % in 10 ìÒ paxilline (n = 7). The paxilline-induced changes in spike waveform closely resembled the activity-induced endogenous spike broadening (compare Fig. 4C and E). A lower dose of paxilline (2 ìÒ) had similar effects (n = 2, Fig. 4G and H). These results suggest that repetitive firing and paxilline suppressed the same repolarizing current component. The remaining broadening of the later spikes in the presence of IbTX or paxilline (Figs 3D, G and H and 4D, I and J) suggests that channels other than BK also contribute to the activity-induced spike broadening. Calcium-free medium reduced the spike broadening during repetitive firing We next perfused the slices with MnClµ-containing Ca¥-free medium, to prevent BK-channel activation by eliminating
Figure 5. Calcium-free medium reduced the spike broadening during a burst A and B, spike trains (50 ms, 5 spikes) in control and in Ca¥free medium. C and D, perfusion with Ca¥-free medium with 2 mÒ manganese reduced the spike broadening from the 1st spike to the 3rd within a train. E, normalized spike duration in medium with and without Ca¥ (means ± s.e.m., n = 8; *P < 0·05, Student’s two-tailed paired t test).

the Ca¥ influx. As expected, the fAHP was blocked and the rate of spike repolarization was slowed (Fig. 5A—D). In addition, the broadening from the 1st to the 3rd spike was reduced from 49·4 ± 8·7 % (control) to 22·5 ± 5·9 % in Ca¥free medium (n = 8), and there was also a significant decrease in the relative spike broadening of the 2nd and 3rd spikes in Ca¥-free medium (Fig. 5E). Note that the Ca¥-free medium, unlike the specific BKchannel blockers (Figs 3E and 4E), eliminated the ‘shoulder’ during the repolarization. This ‘shoulder’ is probably due to inward Ca¥ currents (Storm, 1987a,b; Lancaster & Nicoll, 1987), whose recruitment may contribute directly to the spike broadening (Aldrich et al. 1979). Computer simulations Since many hypotheses for the functions of ion channels cannot readily be tested experimentally with the available methods, computer simulations were performed to assess the contribution of various current components to spike broadening. We used the reduced compartmental model developed by Borg-Graham (1998), which incorporates 11 active currents and intracellular Ca¥ dynamics (see Methods). A 3-state Markov model represents ICT and includes a voltage-dependent removal of inactivation in order to reproduce the transient presence of ICT over the first few spikes in the train. Based on the experimental finding of a fast transient BK-like current elicited during depolarizing voltage steps (Zbicz & Weight, 1985; Storm, 1987c; Halvorsrud et al. 1999; Shao et al. 1999), the kinetics of ICT were modified to inactivate in response to such voltage steps (see Appendix). Using this modified model, we simulated spike trains in response to 50 ms current pulses, with the current intensities adjusted to elicit five spikes. Comparisons between simulations with transient BK-channels present (Fig. 6A—C), without any BK-channels (Fig. 6D—F), and with noninactivating BK-channels (Fig. 6G—I) support the hypothesis that BK-channel inactivation is important for activitydependent spike broadening. Simulations with a transient BK-channel in the model produced a similar spike train as observed experimentally (compare Fig. 6A, with Fig. 1A). In particular, the fAHP (8) was prominent after the 1st spike, but was strongly reduced after subsequent spikes, and there was substantial spike broadening during repetitive firing (Fig. 6C and J (±)). The model showed that the broadening was largely due to cumulative inactivation of ICT during the spike train (Fig. 6B, continuous line). As ICT declined, the A-current (dashed line) replaced ICT as the main repolarizing current during the last three spikes. When ICT was removed from the model, the fAHP disappeared and the spike broadening was strongly reduced (Fig. 6D, F and J (6)), qualitatively similar to the

